<section class="section bg-cream">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header centered">
            <span class="section-eyebrow">Why Drip for Citrus</span>
            <h2>The Benefits of Precision Citrus Irrigation</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="three-col-grid">
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🍊</div>
                <h3>Fruit Sizing Control</h3>
                <p>Consistent soil moisture during fruit development (June–August for navels) prevents water stress events that cause premature drop and small fruit. SDI growers consistently grade out at 40–56 vs. 48–72 sizes.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🦠</div>
                <h3>Phytophthora Prevention</h3>
                <p>Wet crowns and berms are the primary cause of Phytophthora gummosis in citrus. SDI keeps surface soil dry around the trunk while delivering water precisely to the active root zone 8–18 inches deep.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🧪</div>
                <h3>Zinc &amp; Micronutrient Delivery</h3>
                <p>Citrus has high micronutrient demands that are hard to satisfy with foliar sprays alone. SDI fertigation delivers chelated zinc, manganese, and iron into the root zone at the timing and rate plants need.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🌡️</div>
                <h3>Harvest Timing Flexibility</h3>
                <p>Drip-irrigated citrus orchards can be entered for harvest at any time. No waiting for flood-irrigated berms to dry, and no harvest equipment rutting in wet soil between rows.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🌱</div>
                <h3>Young Tree Establishment</h3>
                <p>New citrus plantings establish faster with drip. Targeted water delivery keeps young feeder roots actively growing without the leaching that can slow establishment in coarse soils.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="highlight-card">
                <div class="highlight-card-icon">📊</div>
                <h3>Grower Result: Tulare Co.</h3>
                <p>A 380-acre navel orange operation switched from sprinklers to SDI and reduced water use from 3.4 to 2.0 AF/acre while improving packout from 68% to 81% of the premium 40–56 sizes.</p>
                <a href="/growers-stories" class="btn-primary-sm" style="margin-top:16px;">More Stories →</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

